Accidental tech billionaires like Craig Newmark?
text:
Are there others like Craig Newmark, who started Craigslist as a free newsletter and seems to have sort of happened into becoming a billionaire.

Craigslist does not seem like it was too focused on scaling or innovating - it only ever had one funding round - and that was after Newmark left as CEO. It really seems like Newmark happened into a viral success and tons of money.

Are there others like this?

Ask HN: Commit suicide (in terms of family time)
text:
So, if you agree to work from the office and on “hardcore” mode, wouldn’t that imply that you are saying goodbye to your family in practical terms?

A simple back of the envelope calculation assuming that “hardcore” means 10h/day instead of the usual 8h/day:

- 10h/day at the office

- 25 min commute each way

- 8h/day of sleep

- 1h/day for chores (shower, dinner, breakfast)

That leaves you 4h/day to spend with your loved ones, plus weekends (unless “hardcore” also means working a little bit on Saturdays. Wouldn’t surprise me). And those 4h won’t be your best hours in the day (you would probably want to sit down at the couch). So anyone staying at Twitter would be committing suicide in terms of family and friends life.

I guess only people without family would consider staying.

Show HN: Intents Operator, turns dev intent into K8s netpolicies and Kafka ACLs
text:
Hey HN,

We’ve recently published an open source Kubernetes operator, the intents operator, that makes it easy to manage network policies and Kafka ACLs in a way that enables teams to control access without cross-team coordination, and keeps gradual rollout in mind, eliminating many points of friction with using network policies and Kafka ACLs.

The intents operator implements a concept called IBAC, or Intents-Based Access Control, for Kubernetes network policies and Kafka ACLs. For network policies, it means that developers that want to connect to another service, declare the intent to do so, and the operator creates appropriate network policies, as well as labeling pods and namespaces as needed.

For example:

  apiVersion: k8s.otterize.com/v1alpha1
  kind: ClientIntents
  metadata:
    name: intents-sample
  spec:
    service:
      name: my-client
    calls:
      - name: web-server
The effect is that a single Kubernetes resource controls access - whereas with network policies, developers, often across multiple teams, must coordinate the contents and versioning of 3 resources - the network policy and labels themselves. We think this approach is a ton easier to reason about and work with, and that’s all us devs really want, right? Just let me get on with it.

We’re building more of this stuff, and think it should be equally easy to get access even when you need to access different kinds of services on different platforms. Securely accessing services shouldn’t be hard - it should be easy to do the right thing and hard to shoot yourself in the foot, and it should work with your existing infrastructure and development workflows.

If you too have felt the pain of managing network policies, have a look and let us know what you think!
